Agent Note: Select all that apply

4 - Pain or swelling in at least 3 separate joints

6 - "Flares" or worsening of your symptoms after putting stress on your joints, like exercising or lifting something heavy

projQuestions.caption: Intro-QS5
projQuestions.questionText:
Alias: Benefits Language - Single Indication Group# MQ8004AMS1 Element# QSI8004 Let's get started to see if there is %INDICATION% that's right for you.

You'll first complete this questionnaire with me right now. You don’t have to answer any questions you don’t want to answer. Your answers will be recorded, but your information will only be used to see if there is a study that's right for you.
Then, if there is a study that's right for you, you’ll schedule an in person visit at the study doctor’s office.
If you attend all required study visits, you may receive:
  • Study medication or placebo, at no-cost to you
  • Study-related care from a local doctor for the length of the study, at no-cost to you
  • And depending on the study, compensation of up to $%COMPENSATION% for time and travel, for qualified participants who complete study related visits

Agent Note: If caller has questions about the process, or availability of sites in their area, read: "If there is a study that's right for you, I’ll let you know which study doctor’s offices in your area are participating in the study, and you can select the one that is most convenient for you. Then we’ll send the study doctor's office your information, so they can get in touch with you to continue the process to make sure you are a match for the study."

If you have any questions, you can contact information@acurian.com.

Element# QS2
Heart failure is also called congestive heart failure or CHF. It is an ongoing health problem. It happens when your heart cannot pump as well as it should. Common symptoms of CHF include: fluid retention, swelling of the feet and ankles, bloating, and difficulty breathing.

Many people with heart failure have a history of other heart problems, like a heart attack or blocked arteries. However, heart failure is a different, specific medical condition. Not everyone who has had a heart attack will develop heart failure.
Has a healthcare professional told you that you have heart failure, congestive heart failure, or CHF?

answerChoices.choiceText: 3 - I have experienced other heart problems, but not CHF

projQuestions.caption: Core-QS39
projQuestions.questionText:
Element# QS3
Symptoms of heart failure include fatigue, racing of the heart, shortness of breath, frequent coughing, and swelling of feet, ankles or legs.
Which of the following best describes how often you have symptoms of heart failure?

answerChoices.choiceText: 1 - I do not have symptoms when going about my normal daily activities
2 - I have some mild symptoms when going about my normal daily activities
3 - I am comfortable sitting or lying down, but have symptoms with very little activity (standing, walking)
4 - I have symptoms even when I am sitting or lying down or with any bit of activity

Alias: Opt-Out Close 1 Element# QSC9032 We are sorry that you do not wish to remain in Acurian's database. We want to make sure you know that your privacy has not been compromised in any way, and that we did not receive your information from your doctor or any other health professional. Acurian sends information to people who we believe may be interested in clinical research opportunities. You may have previously expressed interest in receiving information about this health condition through a survey or on Acurian's website, or you may have been included in our mailing because of generally available demographic information about you, like your age and gender.

[Optional language for CC agents if additional follow-up is necessary:
Acurian receives information from companies who conduct surveys which include health-related information. It is possible that you filled out one of these surveys at some time in the past, even several years ago, and provided permission to be contacted with information about the health concerns that you reported at that time.
It is also possible that you never filled out a survey of this type. Since some medical conditions are more common among certain age groups, you may have been included in a mailing because you live near one of the research centers, and people of your age group and/or gender are more likely to have the condition that is being researched.
I would like to assure you again that we have not received any health information about you from your doctor, insurance company, or any other medical professional. If you are concerned about your privacy I can submit a request for someone from Acurian to follow up and let you know exactly where we received your name.]

Would you like to be removed from our database at this time?

Alias: HealthyMinds Registry Close Element# QSC9116 I also wanted to let you know about the Synexus HealthyMinds Registry, an innovative new study to help researchers understand how healthy brains age in order to identify potential methods of prevention, treatment, and cures for cognitive decline, Alzheimer’s Disease, and other forms of dementia.

Participation in the study is easy, free, done entirely online, and includes brain-training games to exercise the mind and help maintain mental ability. When the study launches, space will be limited, and only United States residents 50 years old or older who have access to the Internet and have not been diagnosed with dementia will be able to participate.

Alias: arthritis Element# QS537 What kind of arthritis do you have?
Agent Note: Select all that apply

answerChoices.choiceText: 1 - Osteoarthritis, the most common form of arthritis, caused by wear and tear on the joints due to aging
2 - Rheumatoid arthritis, a serious medical condition caused by your immune system attacking your joints
3 - Psoriatic Arthritis
4 - Ankylosing Spondylitis

projQuestions.caption: RA_2821-QS6
projQuestions.questionText:
Element# QS505
Which of the following best describes how your RA symptoms started for the very first time?

answerChoices.choiceText: 1 - Symptoms started suddenly; within less than a  month, I went from feeling fine to having joint pain or other symptoms
2 - Symptoms took several months to develop; the pain built gradually over a period of time
4 - Symptoms developed over a long period of time following an old injury; the injured joint has always bothered me from time to  time, but has gotten much worse with age

projQuestions.caption: RA_2821-QS7
projQuestions.questionText:
Element# QS506 What tests did you have that led to your doctor diagnosing your Rheumatoid Arthritis?
Agent Note: Select all that apply

answerChoices.choiceText: 1 - A blood test that was positive for rheumatoid factor or rheumatoid arthritis
2 - An x-ray of your affected joints, which included multiple joints such as your hands and feet
3 - An x-ray of your affected joint, which included one large joint such as one of your knees, hips, or elbows
4 - An examination of your affected joints by a medical professional

projQuestions.caption: RA_2821-QS9

Element# QS508 Are you currently experiencing any of the following joint symptoms associated with your RA?
Agent Note: Select all that apply

answerChoices.choiceText: 1 - Difficulty  making a fist because your hands are stiff or swollen
2 - Joints are very stiff in the morning - you may have difficulty getting out of bed or require a very long time to get dressed
3 - Pain or swelling in the small joints of your hands or feet
4 - Pain or swelling in at least 3 separate joints
5 - "Flares" of symptoms from time to time that seem to come out of nowhere
6 - "Flares" or worsening of your symptoms after putting stress on your joints, like exercising or lifting something heavy

projQuestions.questionText:
Element# QS4402 Do you experience either of the following types of urinary leakage, sometimes called urinary incontinence?
Agent Note: Select all that apply

answerChoices.choiceText: 1 - Stress urinary leakage - leaking of urine while coughing, sneezing, laughing, jumping, or performing other activities that put pressure on the bladder
2 - Urge urinary leakage - strong, urgent need to urinate, accidents in which you are unable to reach a bathroom in time, and occasional bed-wetting

projQuestions.caption: SUI-QS3
projQuestions.questionText:
Element# QS4403
To review, stress urinary leakage is associated with physical activities such as coughing, sneezing, and laughing, while urge urinary leakage is associated with sudden, intense urges to urinate.
Which type of urinary leakage do you experience most often?

answerChoices.choiceText: 3 - I experience stress and urge leakage equally / about the same

projQuestions.caption: SUI-QS4
projQuestions.questionText:
Element# QS4404
How long have you been experiencing urinary leakage?

projQuestions.caption: SUI-QS5
projQuestions.questionText: Element# QS4405 During a typical day, how frequently do you experience urinary leakage?

answerChoices.choiceText: 1 - Less than once per day (some days I experience it, while other days I do not)

projQuestions.caption: SUI-QS6
projQuestions.questionText:
Element# QS4406 Have you ever used any of the following therapies to treat urinary leakage?
Agent Note: Select all that apply

answerChoices.choiceText: 1 - Behavioral modifications - reducing fluid or caffeine intake, toilet mapping (plotting out the location of public and private toilet facilities)
2 - Pelvic floor exercises - Kegel or other pelvic muscle exercises designed to improve bladder control and reduce or stop leakage of urine
3 - Biofeedback - Q-tip test, manometry, or electromyography (EMG)
4 - Electrical stimulation - electrodes send mild electric currents to nerves in the lower back or pelvic muscles that control urination
5 - Urethral bulking - material such as collagen or a water-based gel is injected around the urethra; this narrows the urethra so leakage is less likely to occur

projQuestions.caption: SUI-QS7
projQuestions.questionText:
Element# QS4407 Have you ever had any of the following pelvic surgeries or procedures?
Agent Note: Select all that apply

answerChoices.choiceText: 1 - Urethral sling - a sling is placed around the urethra to lift it back into a normal position, and to exert pressure to aid in urine retention
2 - Culposuspension - a surgical procedure that provides support for the bladder
3 - Surgery for urethral diverticulum (a "pocket" that forms in the vaginal wall next to the urethra)
4 - Pelvic radiation - uses high-energy beams to treat certain pelvic conditions
5 - Anterior prolapse or cystocele repair - a surgical procedure used to correct bulging of the bladder into the vagina
6 - Artificial urinary sphincter - a device with a hand-controlled pump that allows you to control your bladder by compressing and releasing a cuff around the urethra
7 - Vaginal rejuvenation or MonaLisa Touch - laser treatment for vaginal atrophy

Alias: NEW - R56 Element# QS4715 Have you been diagnosed with ankylosing spondylitis, or AS, by a doctor? (Agent Note: ANK-kih-low-sing spon-dill-LITE-iss)
Ankylosing spondylitis is a chronic inflammatory disease that primarily affects the spine, leading to frequent back pain and stiffness and sometimes pain in other areas of the body, too.  The back pain is usually worse in the morning and after periods of rest or inactivity.  In advanced cases, inflammation can cause sections of the spine to fuse together and become less flexible.

projQuestions.caption: IBD-QS8
projQuestions.questionText:
Element# QS5729 As part of your diagnosis, have you ever had any of the following procedures done? Please select all that apply.
Agent Note: Select all that apply

answerChoices.choiceText: 1 - Endoscopy - a thin, flexible, lighted tube is inserted through the mouth. This allows the doctor to look for abnormal areas. A biopsy is sometimes taken during this test.

2 - Colonoscopy – a thin, flexible, lighted tube is inserted through the rectum and into the entire colon (large intestine). This allows the doctor to look for abnormal areas. A biopsy is sometimes taken during this test.

3 - Sigmoidoscopy - a thin, flexible, lighted tube is inserted through the rectum and into the section of the colon (large intestine) closest to the rectum. This allows the doctor to look for abnormal areas. A biopsy is sometimes taken during this test.

projQuestions.caption: IBD-QS10
projQuestions.questionText:
Alias: Steroid Medication for IBD Element# QS5707 Have you ever taken steroid medications for your Crohn's or colitis? 
These include medications like prednisone (Agent Note: PRED-nis-own) or hydrocortisone (Agent Note: hi-dro-CORT-i-sone), usually taken by mouth or sometimes as an enema or injection.

projQuestions.caption: IBD-QS11
projQuestions.questionText:
Alias: Anti-inflammatory Medications for IBD Element# QS5708 Have you ever taken any of the following medications for your Crohn's or colitis? 
Agent Note: Select all that apply

answerChoices.choiceText: 1 - Mesalamine (Agent Note: MEZ-uh-luh-meen) medications, which include Apriso, Asacol, Canasa, Delzicol, Lialda, Pentasa, and Rowasa
2 - Azulfidine, also known as sulfasalazine (Agent Note: ay-ZULF-i-deen, sulf-uh-SAL-uh-zeen)
3 - Colazal or Giazo, also known as balsalazide (Agent Note: COLE-uh-zal, gee-AH-zo, bal-SAL-uh-zide)
4 - Dipentum, also known as olsalazine (Agent Note: di-PENT-um, ol-SAL-uh-zeen)

projQuestions.caption: IBD-QS12
projQuestions.questionText:
Alias: Immunosuppressants for IBD Element# QS5709 Have you ever treated your Crohn's or colitis with any of the following medications that suppress your immune system? 
Agent Note: Select all that apply

answerChoices.choiceText: 1 - Astagraf, Envarsus, or Prograf, also known as tacrolimus (Agent Note: tah-CRO-li-mus)
2 - Azasan or Imuran, also known as azathioprine (Agent Note: AY-zuh-san, IM-you-ran, ay-zuh-THI-o-prin)
3 - CellCept or Myfortic, also known as mycophenolate (Agent Note: my-co-FEN-o-late)
5 - Methotrexate pills or tablets, also known as Rheumatrex or Trexall (Agent Note: ROOM-uh-trex)
6 - Methotrexate injections or shots, also known as Otrexup or Rasuvo (Agent Note: oh-TREX-up, ruh-SOO-vo)
7 - Purixan, also known as 6-MP or mercaptopurine (Agent Note: pure-RIX-an, mer-capt-oh-PURE-een)
8 - Rapamune, also known as sirolimus (Agent Note: RAP-uh-mune, sir-OH-li-mus)
9 - Sandimmune, Gengraf, or Neoral, also known as cyclosporine (Agent Note: GEN-graf, NEE-oh-ral, cy-clo-SPOR-in)

projQuestions.caption: IBD-QS13
projQuestions.questionText:
Alias: Biologics Element# QS5710 "Biologics" are medications that affect the body's immune system. They are given as an infusion (into a vein) or a shot (injection).

Agent Notes:
  • Please read the full list of medications to the respondent
  • Select all that apply

answerChoices.choiceText: 10 - Prolia or Xgeva (Agent Note: PRO-lee-uh, ex-GEE-vuh)

Alias: Flare Question - NEW R72 Element# QS5730
People with Crohn’s disease or ulcerative colitis usually go through periods when the disease is quiet and few or no symptoms are present, alternating with times when it is active and causing symptoms. When symptoms reappear, this is sometimes called a flare or flare-up.
How would you describe your Crohn’s or colitis currently?

answerChoices.choiceText: 1 - In remission (no symptoms, or symptoms do not interfere with daily activities)
4 - Severe symptoms that make life difficult

projQuestions.caption: Heart_Failure-QS2
projQuestions.questionText:
Element# QS6402
Heart failure is also called congestive heart failure or CHF. It is an ongoing health problem. It happens when your heart cannot pump as well as it should.

Many people with heart failure have a history of other heart problems, like a heart attack or blocked arteries. However, heart failure is a different, specific medical condition. Not everyone who has had a heart attack will develop heart failure.
Has a healthcare professional told you that you have heart failure, congestive heart failure, or CHF?

answerChoices.choiceText: 3 - I have experienced other heart problems, but not CHF

projQuestions.caption: Heart_Failure-QS3
projQuestions.questionText:

Symptoms of heart failure include fatigue or feeling tired, rapid heartbeat, shortness of breath or difficulty breathing, frequent coughing, and swelling of feet, ankles or legs.
Which of the following best describes how often you have symptoms of heart failure?

answerChoices.choiceText: 1 - I do not have any symptoms when going about my normal daily activities
2 - I have some mild symptoms when going about my normal daily activities
3 - I am comfortable sitting or lying down, but have symptoms with very little activity (standing, walking)
4 - I have symptoms even when I am sitting or lying down or with any bit of activity

2 - Guttate - Small, pink-red spots appear on your skin
3 - Pustular - White blisters surrounded by red, irritated skin
4 - Erythrodermic - Redness that covers large areas of your skin
5 - Inverse - Skin redness and irritation occurs in the armpits, groin, and in areas of overlapping skin
